(1297, 4484, 'common_questions', '[:en]<p><strong>Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: Where should the Gas Sensors installed?</p>\r\n<p>A: The location of the gas sensor depends on the type of gas used.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Natural gas (NG)</strong> is lighter than air; hence the detector should be located over the topmost window or door aperture, but no more than 30 cm beneath the ceiling level.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG)</strong> is heavier than air; hence the detector should be located below the level where a potential gas leak may occur and no more than 30 cm above floor level.</p>\r\n<p>The NG or LPG detectors should be located 1 to 4 meters from the gas shut off unit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: The Shut off Unit works on batteries. What is the life time of the batteries?</p>\r\n<p>A: The life time of the batteries depends on the number of times the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> Shut Off Unit is being used.  With normal usage profile, the batteries can last up to 3 years.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What standards do the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with?</p>\r\n<p>A: The NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with CE, EN60335-1, EN61010-1, EN50270, EN300, EN301, EN50194-1, and ISO 9001.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How many Gas sensors can I use with a single Shut Off Unit?</p>\r\n<p>A: Each Gas Shut Off Unit can work with up to 6 various Gas sensors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What happens to the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> during a power outage?</p>\r\n<p>A: The Shut oOf Unit works on batteries; hence it is indifference to power outage.  However, the Gas Sensors require AC power, and will not operate during power outage.  In such a case, the communication between the sensors and the Shut Off Unit will not function.  Due to regulation and safety considerations, loss of communication will cause the Gas valve to be automatically shut off.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How can I make sure the system is properly installed and connected?</p>\r\n<p>A: A green communication light on a Gas sensor indicates the existence of proper communication with the Shut-off Unit.<br />\r\nIt is recommended that the system be routinely checked.  Press the “TEST” button on the Gas sensor for a few seconds.  The sensor will make a sound alarm and will send a wireless signal to the Shut off Unit to close the gas valve.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How can I manually turn off the Gas supply by using the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> system?</p>\r\n<p>A: There are two options: (1) On the Shut Off Unit, press the “Close” button; or (2) On one of the Gas sensors, press the “TEST” button for a few seconds.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Triple+ NWL™</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: The Shut off Unit works on batteries. What is the life time of the batteries?</p>\r\n<p>A: The life time of the batteries depends on the number of times the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> shut off unit is being used.  With normal usage profile, the batteries can last up to 2 years.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How will I know that it’s time for batteries replacement?</p>\r\n<p>A: There is a LED indication on the Controller when the Shut Off Unit batteries are low.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What standards do the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> complies with?</p>\r\n<p>A: The Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> complies with CE, EN50270, EN300, EN301, and ISO9001.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What infrastructure is required in order to install the NWL<sup>TM</sup> leakage prevention system?</p>\r\n<p>A: The system comprises on wirelessly, battery operated elements.  Therefore, there is no need for electrical wiring or special infrastructure changes.  Just connect the Shut off Unit to the water piping, synchronize the various elements – and you are all set.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: Where should the Flood Detectors installed?</p>\r\n<p>A: The wireless flood sensor should be installed in places where high chance of water flooding may occur.  E.g. near the washing machine, under the sink, under the boiler, etc.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: Can the system be automatically controlled by an alarm system?</p>\r\n<p>A: Yes.  There is an option to connect the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> Control Unit directly to the premise’s alarm system.  Once leaving the premise, and when the alarm is turned on, the system will automatically shut off the water supply – preventing possible leakage when nobody is present.  Once the alarm system is turned off, the system will seamlessly re-open the water valve.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q:   What certifications does an installer require?</p>\r\n<p>A: Installation of the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> requires a certified technician.  Triple+ provides courses to train its technicians, and makes sure that each installer is familiar with the system and the installation/maintenance procedures.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How many flood detectors can be used with a single Shut Off Unit?</p>\r\n<p>A: Each Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> Shut off Unit can work with up to 10 flood detectors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What happens to the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> system during a power outage?</p>\r\n<p>A: The Shut Off Unit, the Flood Sensors, and the Control Unit all work on batteries (or backed up by batteries), hence it is indifference to power outage.  It is important to make sure that there are back-up batteries in the Control Unit (which is normally connected to an AC/DC converter or gets its power from an alarm system).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How can I make sure the system is properly installed and connected?</p>\r\n<p>A: A green communication light on the Control Unit indicates the existence of proper communication with the Shut Off Unit and/or the Flood Detectors.<br />\r\nIt is recommended that the system be routinely checked.  Press the “Close” button on the Control Unit and make sure that the valve is being opened.  Press the “Open” button and make sure the valve is being opened.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How can I manually turn off the water supply by using the Triple+ NWL<sup>TM</sup> system?</p>\r\n<p>A: There are two options: (1) On the Shut Off Unit, manually rotate the handle; or (2) On the Control Unit, press the “Open” or “Close” buttons.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: Where should the Gas Sensors installed?</p>\r\n<p>A: The location of the gas sensor depends on the type of gas used.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Natural gas (NG)</strong> is lighter than air; hence the detector should be located over the topmost window or door aperture, but no more than 30 cm beneath the ceiling level.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG)</strong> is heavier than air; hence the detector should be located below the level where a potential gas leak may occur and no more than 30 cm above floor level.</p>\r\n<p>The NG or LPG detectors should be located 1 to 4 meters from the gas shut off unit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: The Shut off Unit works on batteries. What is the life time of the batteries?</p>\r\n<p>A: The life time of the batteries depends on the number of times the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> Shut Off Unit is being used.  With normal usage profile, the batteries can last up to 3 years.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What standards do the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with?</p>\r\n<p>A: The NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with CE, EN60335-1, EN61010-1, EN50270, EN300, EN301, EN50194-1, and ISO 9001.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How many Gas sensors can I use with a single Shut Off Unit?</p>\r\n<p>A: Each Gas Shut Off Unit can work with up to 6 various Gas sensors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: What happens to the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> during a power outage?</p>\r\n<p>A: The Shut oOf Unit works on batteries; hence it is indifference to power outage.  However, the Gas Sensors require AC power, and will not operate during power outage.  In such a case, the communication between the sensors and the Shut Off Unit will not function.  Due to regulation and safety considerations, loss of communication will cause the Gas valve to be automatically shut off.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q: How can I make sure the system is properly installed and connected?</p>\r\n<p>A: A green communication light on a Gas sensor indicates the existence of proper communication with the Shut-off Unit.<br />\r\nIt is recommended that the system be routinely checked.  Press the “TEST” button on the Gas sensor for a few seconds.  The sensor will make a sound alarm and will send a wireless signal to the Shut off Unit to close the gas valve.</p>\r\n[:he]<strong>Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nQ: Where should the Gas Sensors installed?\r\n\r\nA: The location of the gas sensor depends on the type of gas used.\r\n\r\n<strong>Natural gas (NG)</strong> is lighter than air; hence the detector should be located over the topmost window or door aperture, but no more than 30 cm beneath the ceiling level.\r\n\r\n<strong>Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG)</strong> is heavier than air; hence the detector should be located below the level where a potential gas leak may occur and no more than 30 cm above floor level.\r\n\r\nThe NG or LPG detectors should be located 1 to 4 meters from the gas shut off unit.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nQ: The Shut off Unit works on batteries. What is the life time of the batteries?\r\n\r\nA: The life time of the batteries depends on the number of times the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> Shut Off Unit is being used.  With normal usage profile, the batteries can last up to 3 years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nQ: What standards do the Triple+ NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with?\r\n\r\nA: The NGL<sup>TM</sup> complies with CE, EN60335-1, EN61010-1, EN50270, EN300, EN301, EN50194-1, and ISO 9001.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nQ: How many Gas sensors can I use with a single Shut Off Unit?\r\n\r\nA: Each Gas Shut Off Unit can work with up to 6 various Gas sensors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;